{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:31:25.725283+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "successfully downloaded text file (SHA: 890470cbcd8b22c382d09c9d7ffd222ed613ce36)", "id": "lc_92738779-386a-4860-b243-0b49cd4e23b2"}, {"type": "text", "text": "#!/usr/bin/env bash\n# Apply all SQL files under migrations/ to the running pgdev container.\n# Order: filename glob, lexicographic.\nset -euo pipefail\n\nCONTAINER=\"${PGDEV_CONTAINER:-pgdev_db}\"\nDB_USER=\"${POSTGRES_USER:-app}\"\nDB_NAME=\"${POSTGRES_DB:-app}\"\n\n# Note: relies on shell glob expansion ordering, not on `find`.\n# Tested on bash and zsh with default LC_COLLATE.\nfor f in migrations/*.sql; do\n    echo \"Applying $f\"\n    docker exec -i \"$CONTAINER\" psql -U \"$DB_USER\" -d \"$DB_NAME\" < \"$f\"\ndone\n", "id": "lc_c35190d8-f8ec-4c6e-941f-b6d85f399b41"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "e30c5353-c5be-4b5c-91f6-568e807b58bd", "tool_call_id": "call_5a257cea6f4044fca0e58e00", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:31:41.262999+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Here's the full walkthrough of the database migrations in this repo.\n\n---\n\n## Migration Infrastructure\n\nMigrations live in the `migrations/` directory and are applied by `scripts/apply_migrations.sh`, which iterates over `migrations/*.sql` in **lexicographic filename order** (the numeric prefixes `001_`, `002_`, `003_` … guarantee the intended sequence).\n\nA historical log of every migration ever run in production is kept in `MIGRATION_HISTORY.md` at the repo root.\n\n---\n\n## Migrations Present in the Directory (applied in order)\n\n### 1. `001_create_users.sql` — *Initial users table*\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE users (\n    id           BIGSERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n    email        TEXT UNIQUE NOT NULL,\n    display_name TEXT,\n    created_at   TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now()\n);\n```\n\n**What it does:** Creates the foundational `users` table with an auto-incrementing `id`, a unique `email`, an optional `display_name`, and an automatic `created_at` timestamp.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `002_create_sessions.sql` — *Sessions table with foreign key*\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE sessions (\n    id          UUID PRIMARY KEY,\n    user_id     BIGINT NOT NULL REFERENCES users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n    issued_at   TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now(),\n    expires_at  TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL\n);\n```\n\n**What it does:** Creates a `sessions` table. Each session is identified by a UUID and tied to a `users` row via a foreign key. Sessions cascade-delete when the owning user is removed, and carry issuance/expiry timestamps (presumably for token lifecycle management).\n\n---\n\n### 3. `003_add_session_index.sql` — *Index on sessions.user_id*\n\n```sql\nCREATE INDEX idx_sessions_user_id ON sessions(user_id);\n```\n\n**What it does:** Adds a B-tree index on `sessions.user_id` to speed up lookups of all sessions belonging to a given user (e.g. \"list active sessions\" or \"revoke all sessions for user X\").\n\n---\n\n## Historical Migrations (run but no longer in `migrations/`)\n\nThe `MIGRATION_HISTORY.md` file records three additional migrations that were applied in deployed environments but whose SQL files have been **archived out** of the `migrations/` directory (the doc notes they may temporarily live in `migrations/archived/`):\n\n| # | File | What it does |\n|---|------|-------------|\n| 4 | `004_partition_users.sql` | Range-partitions the `users` table by `created_at` on a monthly interval. |\n| 5 | `005_archive_legacy_sessions.sql` | Moves sessions older than 90 days into a `sessions_archive` table. |\n| 6 | `006_grant_readonly_role.sql` | Creates a `app_readonly` database role and grants it read-only access. |\n\nThese have already been applied to production and are recorded for audit/on-call reference, but you won't find the SQL files in the current `migrations/` directory.\n\n---\n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n- **3 migration files** are currently checked into the `migrations/` directory; the other 3 have been archived.\n- The schema so far is simple: **users** ↔ **sessions** (one-to-many), with an index on the FK and a partitioning/archival strategy applied over time.\n- The migration runner is a straightforward shell script — no ORM or migration framework, just sorted SQL files piped into `psql`.", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 784, "prompt_tokens": 9091, "total_tokens": 9875, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": 0, "reasoning_tokens": 14, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null, "image_tokens": 0}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": 0, "cached_tokens": 8384, "cache_write_tokens": 0, "video_tokens": 0}, "cost": 0, "is_byok": true, "cost_details": {"upstream_inference_cost": 0.0010198074, "upstream_inference_prompt_cost": 0.0003377274, "upstream_inference_completions_cost": 0.00068208}}, "model_provider": "openai", "model_name": "xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-20260422", "system_fingerprint": null, "id": "gen-1780864285-9Kiwv1VFyVeuxf4eVuMt", "finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "type": "ai", "name": null, "id": "lc_run--019ea3c8-7c1e-7d93-97a0-0dbbbf3c283a-0", "tool_calls": [], "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 9091, "output_tokens": 784, "total_tokens": 9875, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 8384}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 14}}}}]}}}
